Introduction: Quiz Form

The quiz form contains 5 demographic questions and 10 covid19-related questions. I have gotten 33 responses from 17 males and 16 females. Note: If I had the chance to make an improvement on this quiz, I would add more continuous-valued demographic questions and specify the targeted population more accurately.

Demographic Questions

Gender : Nominal
Age : Interval
Residence Location : Nominal
Ethnicity : Nominal
Education : Ordinal

Quiz Questions, Answers & Response rates

A. Data visualization and descriptive stats

1. Gender-based Data visualization

  • Displaying Count of each gender using Pie-chart
ggplot(covid19.data, aes(x=factor(length(covid19.data)), fill=Gender))+
  geom_bar(width = 1)+
  coord_polar("y") + xlab(" ") + geom_text(aes(label=..count..),
              vjust=1,stat='count',
              position = "stack")

  • Displaying the distribution of Total.score for each Gender. It shows Min,Q1,Median,Q3,MAX
ggplot(data=covid19.data, aes(x=Gender, y=Total.score, color=Gender)) + geom_boxplot(varwidth = TRUE)

# The graph shows that : Females have better Median total.score than Males. Also, It tells that Females has narrower Interquartile range than Males.

2. Age-based Data visualization

  • Displaying Count of the People in each Age interval using bar-chart
ggplot(data = covid19.data ,aes(x=Age))+geom_bar() + geom_text(aes(label=..count..),
              vjust=1,stat='count',
              position = "stack")

  • Displaying the distribution of Total.score for each Age-interval. It shows Min,Q1,Median,Q3,MAX
ggplot(data=covid19.data, aes(x=Age, y=Total.score, color=Age)) + geom_boxplot(varwidth = TRUE)

# Graph Description:
# Regardless of the count of records in each age interval,
# The graph shows that :
# Median(18-24 years old) = Median(Over 55 years old)
# Median(18-24 years old) > Median(25-34 years old)
# Median(25-34 years old) > Median(35-44 years old)
# Also, It tells that,
# IQR(18-24 years old) < IQR(25-34 years old)

B. Confidence intervals

# The following function will be called later to return
# a summary of f1 based on f2.
getSummaryTable <- function(f1,f2,f.label) {
  df <- data.frame()
  value <- aggregate(f1 ~ f2,data = covid19.data,
          FUN = function(x) {c(mean = mean(x),
                               lower.ci = t.test(x)$conf.int[1],
                               upper.ci = t.test(x)$conf.int[2])});
  return(value)}



1. Confidence intervals for Total.score based on Gender

# Getting the summary of Total.score based on Gender
ts.summary  <- getSummaryTable (Total.score, Gender);

# To get rid of the inner data.frame in ts.summary and include its vectors to main data.frame.
ts.summary <- do.call(data.frame, ts.summary)

# Renaming the colum.names
colnames(ts.summary) <- c('gender','mean','lower.ci','upper.ci')

# Show the summary
print(ts.summary)
##   gender     mean lower.ci upper.ci
## 1 Female 79.37500 72.78565 85.96435
## 2   Male 72.94118 63.02378 82.85858
# Plotting
ggplot(ts.summary, aes(
              ts.summary$gender,ts.summary$mean,fill=ts.summary$gender)) + 
geom_bar(aes(y=ts.summary$mean),position = "dodge", stat="identity", width=0.5) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=ts.summary$lower.ci,
                    ymax=ts.summary$upper.ci),
                width=0.2,position = position_dodge(0.3)) + 
  ylab("Mean of Total Score") + 
  xlab("Gender")

#Graph Description:
# The graph shows that:
# Mean(total.score of Females) is greater than Mean(total.score of Males)
# confidence.interval(total.score of Males) is wider than confidence.interval(total.score of Females)

C. Hypothesis testing



1. (One sample t.test)

Test if the Mean of Total.score is lower than 70.
  • Null hypothesis(H0): mean(Total.score) <= 70
  • Alternative hypothesis(Ha): mean(Total.score) > 70
# Shapiro-Wilk normality test
shapiro.test(Total.score) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Total.score
## W = 0.94402, p-value = 0.08898
# Result of shapiro.test: The data are normally distributed. Because P.value > 0.05.

# t-test of the Hypothesis
t.test(Total.score,mu=70,alternative="greater")
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Total.score
## t = 2.1252, df = 32, p-value = 0.02069
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is greater than 70
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  71.23006      Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  76.06061
# Result of t.test: We reject null hypothesis becasue p.value < 0.05



2. (Two independent sample t.test)

Test if Mean of Total.score based on Gender is significantly different.


Hypothesis
+ Null hypothesis(H0): mu(male.total.score) = mu(female.total.score)
+ Alternative hypothesis(Ha): mu(male.total.score) != mu(female.total.score)

# Shapiro-Wilk normality test
covid19.males <- (covid19.data[Gender == 'Male',])
covid19.females <- (covid19.data[Gender == 'Female',])

shapiro.test(covid19.males$Total.score) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  covid19.males$Total.score
## W = 0.93706, p-value = 0.2849
shapiro.test(covid19.females$Total.score) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  covid19.females$Total.score
## W = 0.93101, p-value = 0.253
# Result of shapiro.test: The data are normally distributed. Because P.value > 0.05 for both tests.

# Checking Variance homogenity
var.test(covid19.males$Total.score, covid19.females$Total.score)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  covid19.males$Total.score and covid19.females$Total.score
## F = 2.4331, num df = 16, denom df = 15, p-value = 0.09265
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.8579133 6.7822595
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           2.433082
# Result of var.test: The Variances are homogeneous. Because P.value > 0.05.

# t-test of the Hypothesis
t.test(covid19.males$Total.score,covid19.females$Total.score,conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  covid19.males$Total.score and covid19.females$Total.score
## t = -1.1474, df = 27.443, p-value = 0.2611
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -17.930605   5.062958
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  72.94118  79.37500
# Result of t.test: We can't reject null hypothesis becasue p.value > 0.05



3. (Two independenet sample t.test)

Test if Mean of Total.score based on 2 Categories of Age Categories is significantly different.

Note that: Age has 6 Groups. I picked two groups.
a. group1: 18-24 years old
b. group2: 25-34 years old

Hypothesis
+ Null hypothesis(H0): mu(group1.total.score) = mu(group2.total.score)
+ Alternative hypothesis(Ha): mu(group1.total.score) != mu(group2.total.score)

# Shapiro-Wilk normality test
covid19.group1 <- (covid19.data[Age == '18-24 years old',])
covid19.group2 <- (covid19.data[Age == '25-34 years old',])

shapiro.test(covid19.group1$Total.score) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  covid19.group1$Total.score
## W = 0.91133, p-value = 0.05833
shapiro.test(covid19.group2$Total.score) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  covid19.group2$Total.score
## W = 0.98259, p-value = 0.9637
# Result of shapiro.test: The data are normally distributed. Because P.value > 0.05 for both tests.

# Checking Variance homogenity
var.test(covid19.group1$Total.score, covid19.group2$Total.score)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  covid19.group1$Total.score and covid19.group2$Total.score
## F = 0.61327, num df = 20, denom df = 5, p-value = 0.3954
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.09690447 2.01706384
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##          0.6132653
# Result of var.test: The Variances are homogeneous. Because P.value > 0.05.

# t-test of the Hypothesis
t.test(covid19.group1$Total.score, covid19.group2$Total.score, conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  covid19.group1$Total.score and covid19.group2$Total.score
## t = 0.49807, df = 6.8531, p-value = 0.634
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -17.94404  27.46785
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  78.09524  73.33333
# Result of t.test: We can't reject null hypothesis becasue p.value > 0.05




D. ANOVA – Analysis of variance



1. Testing if Total.score mean is equal between 3 of the Age intervals

I ignored the 4th Age interval(“over 55 years old”) because it has only one record associated with it, It failed while checking Normality and variance homogenety.
##step(0) -- Getting needed age levels from covid19.data
df <- covid19.data[Age != 'Over 55',]
unique(df$Age)
## [1] 25-34 years old 18-24 years old 35-44 years old
## Levels: 18-24 years old 25-34 years old 35-44 years old Over 55
#step(1) -- formulate the hypothesis
#H0: μ(18-24 years old) = μ(25-34 years old) = μ(35-44 years old) = μ(Over 55)  
#Ha: μ(i) are not all equal

#step(2) -- 
# Response -> y: total.score
# Factor   -> x: Age

#step(3) -- Visualisation
# a. Create a box plot that shows MIN,Q1,MEDIAN,Q3,MAX and IQR
boxplot(df$Total.score ~ df$Age, data = df)

# b. Create a line plot that shows
#1. data dot plots
#2. mean standard error.
#3. A linking line between means.

ggline(df, x = "Age", y = "Total.score", 
       add = c("mean_se", "jitter"))

#step(4) -- Assumptions
# 4.1-  Testing Normality
age.a <- df[df$Age == '18-24 years old',]
age.a <- age.a$Total.score
shapiro.test(age.a)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  age.a
## W = 0.91133, p-value = 0.05833
# Result p.value(0.05833) > 0.5    :: Normal

age.b <- df[df$Age == '25-34 years old',]
age.b <- age.b$Total.score
shapiro.test(age.b)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  age.b
## W = 0.98259, p-value = 0.9637
# Result p.value(0.9637) > 0.5    :: Normal

age.c <- df[df$Age == '35-44 years old',]
age.c <- age.c$Total.score
shapiro.test(age.c)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  age.c
## W = 0.88349, p-value = 0.3254
# Result p.value(0.3254) > 0.5    :: Normal

# 4.2- Variance Homogenety
#H0: var(18-24 years old) = var(25-34 years old) = var(35-44 years old)
#Ha: var(i) are not all equal
bartlett.test(df$Total.score ~ df$Age, data= df)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  df$Total.score by df$Age
## Bartlett's K-squared = 4.0695, df = 2, p-value = 0.1307
# Result: p-value(0.1307)>0.05 which means H0 isn't rejected.
# We can assume the Variances are Homogeneous.
# step(5) -- Analysis of variance
res.aov <- aov(df$Total.score ~ df$Age, data=df)
summary(res.aov)
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## df$Age       2    315   157.4   0.553  0.581
## Residuals   29   8257   284.7
# As the p-value(0.580) is greater than 0.05, we can't reject the null hypothesis. We can assume that the mean of df$age intervals are equal. So, we don't have to continue to find the means that are different to each other

# optional step for comparing multiple pairwise using Tukey
TukeyHSD(res.aov)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = df$Total.score ~ df$Age, data = df)
## 
## $`df$Age`
##                                      diff       lwr      upr     p adj
## 25-34 years old-18-24 years old -4.761905 -24.05258 14.52877 0.8160319
## 35-44 years old-18-24 years old -8.095238 -28.83209 12.64162 0.6049470
## 35-44 years old-25-34 years old -3.333333 -28.56736 21.90069 0.9431365
# The p-value between each pairs in the result, proves the fact that the mean of Total.score of age intervales are equal.



2. Testing if Total.score mean is equal between Residence.Locations

##step(0) -- Getting needed Residence.Locations from covid19.data
df <- covid19.data[Residence.Location != 'Other' ,]

# Show the df current levels
unique(df$Residence.Location)
## [1] Asia   Europe Africa
## Levels: Africa Asia Europe Other
#step(1) -- formulate the hypothesis
#H0: μ(Africa) = μ(Asia) = μ(Europe)    
#Ha: μ(i) are not all equal

# a. step(2) -- 
# Response -> y: total.score
# Factor   -> x: Residence.Location


# b. step(3) -- Visualisation
# Create a box plot that shows MIN,Q1,MEDIAN,Q3,MAX and IQR.
boxplot(df$Total.score ~ df$Residence.Location, data = df)

#Create a line plot that shows
#1. data dot plots
#2. mean standard error.
#3. A linking line between means.

ggline(df, x = "Residence.Location", y = "Total.score", 
       add = c("mean_se", "jitter"))

#step(4) -- Assumptions
# 4.1-  Testing Normality
rl.a <- df[df$Residence.Location == 'Africa',]
rl.a <- rl.a$Total.score
shapiro.test(rl.a)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  rl.a
## W = 0.93837, p-value = 0.4362
# Result p.value(0.4362) > 0.5    :: Normal

rl.b <- df[df$Residence.Location == 'Asia',]
rl.b <- rl.b$Total.score
shapiro.test(rl.b)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  rl.b
## W = 0.9694, p-value = 0.8933
# Result p.value(0.8933) > 0.5    :: Normal

rl.c <- df[df$Residence.Location == 'Europe',]
rl.c <- rl.c$Total.score
shapiro.test(rl.c)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  rl.c
## W = 0.89005, p-value = 0.1393
# Result p.value(0.1393) > 0.5    :: Normal

# 4.2- Variance Homogenety
#H0: var(Africa) = var(Asia) = var(Europe)  
#Ha: var(i) are not all equal
bartlett.test(df$Total.score ~ df$Residence.Location, data= df)
## 
##  Bartlett test of homogeneity of variances
## 
## data:  df$Total.score by df$Residence.Location
## Bartlett's K-squared = 3.4776, df = 2, p-value = 0.1757
# Result: p-value(0.1757)>0.05 which means H0 isn't rejected.
# We can assume the Variances are Homogeneous.
# step(5) -- Analysis of variance
res.aov <- aov(df$Total.score ~ df$Residence.Location, data=df)
summary(res.aov)
##                       Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## df$Residence.Location  2    353   176.7    0.67  0.519
## Residuals             29   7643   263.6
# As the p-value(0.519) is greater than 0.05, we can't reject the null hypothesis. We can assume that the mean of df$Residence.Location are all equal. So, we don't have to continue to find the Residence.Locations that are different to each other

# optional step for comparing multiple pairwise using Tukey
TukeyHSD(res.aov)
##   Tukey multiple comparisons of means
##     95% family-wise confidence level
## 
## Fit: aov(formula = df$Total.score ~ df$Residence.Location, data = df)
## 
## $`df$Residence.Location`
##                    diff       lwr       upr     p adj
## Asia-Africa   -5.480769 -23.49740 12.535858 0.7352725
## Europe-Africa -7.412587 -23.83807  9.012894 0.5130261
## Europe-Asia   -1.931818 -20.56195 16.698315 0.9645383
# The p-value between each pairs in the result, proves the fact that the mean of Total.score of Residence.Location categories are equal.
